    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a clear focus on exploiting favorable matchups against higher-xERA arms, headlined by the most compelling start of the day: **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98). While his spot in the 8th hole typically drags down his ceiling, the combination of a generous matchup against Kelly and, crucially, a slow-delivery pitcher who creates an opportunistic environment for **Pete Crow-Armstrong**\u2019s elite speed makes him a must-start. He is joined in high-upside territory by **Junior Caminero** (73.06) and **Trea Turner** (69.27), both of whom capitalize on top-of-the-order positioning and favorable SP skill matchups. **Colt Keith** (65.82) is another pivot to watch, as his ability to leverage Jack Leiter\u2019s slow delivery\u2014bolstered by a +7% platoon advantage\u2014positions him to contribute significantly to our stolen base targets today.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, who sat just outside the cut-off at 42.40. While he offers some platoon value against a lefty like Matz, the optimizer favored the higher defensive and offensive efficiency of our secondary outfielders and the specific speed-based matchup edges inherent to **Pete Crow-Armstrong** and **Hyeseong Kim**. We are proceeding with caution regarding **Kazuma Okamoto** (45.51); despite his talent, he faces a difficult matchup against Ryan (3.39 xERA) and carries a negative BvP flag, making him the most fragile link in today's projection. Meanwhile, **Yordan Alvarez** (60.46) remains an auto-start despite a stiff L/L platoon disadvantage, as his elite 0.430 xwOBA provides an underlying floor that outweighs typical lineup-construction constraints.\n\nRisk mitigation remains a priority as we monitor the lower end of our lineup. **Hyeseong Kim** (55.70) is being started primarily for his speed potential and wind-assisted upside, though he is on a short leash given the 8th-order penalty. We continue to track the status of **Christian Yelich** and **Luke Raley**, who remain unavailable, keeping our depth tested. With the Zebras chasing every marginal stolen base, the presence of **Caleb Durbin** (60.05) in the bottom of the order is an experiment in efficiency; his high SP-skill rating is being weighed against the aggressive -8% penalty for his spot in the batting order. We are positioned to maximize daily cap efficiency by leaning into these speed-optimized profiles.",
